Topic: Tribute Speech 
Tribute Speech Outline  
General Purpose: Tribute Speech 
Specific Purpose: Elizabeth Blackwell 
Thesis: Elizabeth Blackwell has inspired me to pursue my dreams and never stop trying no matter what people 
say or how hard it gets.  
Introduction  
Attention Getter: “None of us knowhow capable we are until we are tested”—Elizabeth Blackwell 
Connection to Audience: Elizabeth Blackwell was an inspiration to society. She changed the face of the 
medical field

ciety. She changed the face of the 
medical field by opening the door to not just women, but everyone with a dream. 
Credibility Statement: My dad was the one who introduced me to Elizabeth Blackwell. She’s been my role 
model ever since I was 10 years old.  
Thesis: Elizabeth Blackwell has inspired me to pursue my dreams and never stop trying no matter what 
people say or how hard it gets. 
Body  
I. Background 
        
A. Family 
1. Elizabeth was part of a large and cultured family. The Black

was part of a large and cultured family. The Blackwell family was denied access to 
public school because of their religious beliefs. Her parents Hannah and Samuel paid for their 
kids to have private tutors.  
2. Samuel passed away and the three oldest girls, including Elizabeth, provided for the family by 
running a boarding school. Elizabeth showed me the importance of always putting family 
first.  
 
        
B. Education 
1. When Elizabeth no longer had to support her family, she started s

no longer had to support her family, she started studying medicine with 
physicians who felt sorry for her. 
2. Later when she felt more comfortable, she applied to medical schools, she was denied by all 
the colleges she applies to besides one, Geneva Medical College. They only let her into 
Geneva as a joke 
3. The joke was on them as she was ranked 1st in her class and was the first women in the United 
States to graduate with a medical career. This showed me that it doesn’t matter what other

. This showed me that it doesn’t matter what others 
think, and that you should always make the best out of a bad situation. 
        
C. Her Inspiration 
1. Never in her life had she thought of practicing medicine. As a woman, she wasn’t even 
allowed to look at a medical book.  
2. She turned to medicine because of a sick friend who told her she would have been spared her   
worst suffering if her physician was a woman. Someone who could have understood her pain. 
This taught me to never fear

nderstood her pain. 
This taught me to never fear new things.  
II. How she has inspired me and others 
        
A. Discrimination 
1. Elizabeth was told by almost everyone in her life that she could not do it because she was only 
a woman, and that medicine was too hard. She was told multiple times to “stick to teaching” 
because people thought that was a more suitable job for a woman. 
2. In her college the male student body constantly harassed, shunned and excluded her. She was 
even barred f

, shunned and excluded her. She was 
even barred from classroom demonstrations. Yet still she pushed through and graduated with 
her medical degree. 
3. Elizabeth taught me and many other women to ignore the negativity and to trust yourself 
above all others. She proved that you can accomplish anything if you put your mind to it and 
to never give up no matter how hard it gets.  
        
B. Overcoming Challenges & Helping Others 
1. Unfortunately, Elizabeth lost vision in one eye and had to giv

y, Elizabeth lost vision in one eye and had to give up on her dream of becoming a 
surgeon. But instead of giving up on medicine she opened a medical college for women which 
provided training and experience for women doctors. 
2. Her primary focus was the injured, the poor and the victims of discrimination. A belief that 
she brought to her college, encouraging her students to care for all, not just the super-rich.  
3. Elizabeth taught me to that in life, it’s important to not only look out fo

at in life, it’s important to not only look out for yourself, but for 
others as well.  
Conclusion 
Summary: Elizabeth changed many women’s lives. She is truly an inspiration who has taught me many  
valuable life lessons.  
Memorable Ending: I would like to see a world full of kindhearted and motivated people. With someone 
like Elizabeth Blackwell as a role model, I truly believe I can help make it happen.
